ce:section.ce:para:
The genotoxic impact of Aegle marmelos derived three different types of CQDs, were further checked by analyzing the molecular interactions of CQDs and the roots tips of Allium sativum at chromosomal level for different concentrations (50, 100, and 250 ppm). Almost similar cytotoxicity and genotoxicity studies was reported earlier but the previous report based on effect of carbon-based nanomaterials has been screened for limited range of concentration i.e. up to 50 ppm only. For each measurement, 1000 cells were scored for both the treated and untreated samples and each measurement is replicate thrice to avoid the error. Different mitotic stages of cells division i.e. interphase, prophase, metaphase, anaphase and telophase were clearly observed in each CQDs treated root tip cells (Fig. 5
                        ). The mitotic and phase indices values were calculated for both the untreated and treated Allium sativum root tip cells with different concentrations (50, 100, and 250 ppm) of C-CQDs, P-CQDs and M-CQDs (Table S1). The obtained mitotic index (MI) value for Allium sativum root tip cells under control condition was found to be 0.812. However, the calculated MI values of Allium sativum root tip cells came out to be 0.679, 0.631 and 0.629 when treated with 50, 100, and 250 ppm concentrations of C-CQDs. The exposure of the Allium sativum root tip cells with 50, 100, and 250 ppm of P-CQDs has produced the mitotic index value of 0.824, 0.739 and 0.724. In addition, the MI values of Allium sativum root tip cells recorded after the treatment with three different concentrations of M-CQDs were 0.578, 0.545 and 0.538. On looking at the data, it has been found that all chosen CQDs have displayed the concentration-based decrement in the MI values as compared to control treatment. The variation in the MI values of CQDs has further been explained due to the changes in the size and charge of the chosen CQDs. For instance, P-CQDs exhibits higher charge as well as lowest size and holds higher impact on MI values followed by C-CQDs and M-CQDs. A concentration -dependent and type-dependent variations on relative mitotic index and phase index values have further been shown in Table S1. Different types of chromosomal aberrations were also apparent along with the mitotic phases in the Allium sativum root tip cells at higher concentration of CQDs. Nevertheless, 50 ppm dosage amount of all types of chosen CQDs have not produced any significant chromosomal aberrations. However, the remarkably induced cell proliferation including existence of laggard, sticky, clumped, bridged types of chromosomes and binucleate cells were observed at 100 and 250 ppm of CQDs (Fig. 6
                        ).
